":"1050","1170":"1170","1070":"1070","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt. 1170–":"circa 1170–Overleden","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","1070–Female":"1070–Overleden","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1050–Male":"1050–Overleden","1051–Female":"1051–Overleden","1190":"1190","Abt. 1170":"circa 1170","1189":"1189","Abt. 1189":"circa 1189","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","1070":"1070","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt. 1170–":"about 1170–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1050–Male":"1050–Deceased","1051–Female":"1051–Deceased","1190":"1190","Abt. 1170":"about 1170","1189":"1189","Abt. 1189":"about 1189","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","1070":"1070","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chudleigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chudley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chudley","meanings":["English: locative name from Chudleigh in Devon."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Chudleigh was born about 1170, in Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Chudleigh, was 122 and his mother, Mrs. Margaret Chudleigh, was 121. He married Thoma de Godelgh in 1189, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt. 1170–":"umbes 1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1051–Female":"1051–Surnud","1190":"1190","Abt. 1170":"umbes 1170","1189":"1189","Abt. 1189":"umbes 1189","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","1070":"1070","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1170–":"noin 1170–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1070–Female":"1070–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1050–Male":"1050–Kuollut","1051–Female":"1051–Kuollut","1190":"1190","Abt. 1170":"noin 1170","1189":"1189","Abt. 1189":"noin 1189","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","11